1. Introduction¶

The main goal of this project is to develop a machine learning model to predict housing prices in Toronto. This project could be useful for real estates as well as investors in housing market. In recent years especially under the shadow of COVID-19 pandemic, the housing prices have experienced considerable fluctuations. Housing prices plunged by the closure of businesses and eventually rocketed up during the re-openings. These unusual factors changed the routine behaviour of the real state market. In this project we tried to develop a model based on recent years’ data to estimate Housing prices in Toronto according to new trends which is based on specific selected features plus the effect of neighbourhood in Toronto. Datasets in this project includes:

  1. Housing dataset
  2. GTA neighbourhoods’ geographical dataset
  3. Neighbourhood profiles’ dataset

After dropping the missing values, the data shrunk by 6,000 However there are still more than 10,000 cases which can be useful for modeling. The next step of cleaning was removing punctuations and clarifying the definition of numeric values:

The next step, would be to remove the punctuations and extract the numeric values from collected stings.

In [11]:
zolo_data['list_price'] = [int(row.replace('$', '').replace('.00','')) for row in zolo_data['list_price']]
zolo_data['sqft'] = [row.replace('sqft', '').replace('+', '').replace('<','') for row in zolo_data['sqft']]
zolo_data['sqft_min'] = [int(row.split('-')[0]) for row in zolo_data['sqft']]
zolo_data['sqft_max'] = [int(row.split('-')[-1]) for row in zolo_data['sqft']]
zolo_data['sqft_avg'] = (zolo_data['sqft_max'] + zolo_data['sqft_min'])/2
zolo_data['Sold on'] = pd.to_datetime(zolo_data['Sold on'])
zolo_data = zolo_data[zolo_data['bathrooms']<10]
zolo_data.drop(['final_price', 'parking'], axis=1, inplace=True)

The ultimate goal is to assign each house data with the mean income of their corresponding neighbourhood.

The neighbourhood profiles database file used in this project was created in 2016 and contains detailed information about education, ethnicity, immigration/citizenship, income, population, etc. in different neighbourhoods. Merging the neighbourhood profile data with the housing data, provides the possibility to assign the mean income of the corresponding neighbourhood to other housing dataset features. In this project, “income data” and “area codes/names” features from the neighbourhood profiles were used.

In [21]:

In our final model, each property should be corresponded to a “mean income value” and a “neighbourhood name”. A visual check on map in following sections indicates that some neighbourhood areas were outside of this project scope and could be removed.

In [26]:
from shapely.geometry import Point, Polygon
from tqdm import tqdm

def find_district(point, df):
    '''
    Returns District name, Area code, and District average income
    '''

    in_shape = []
    for sh in df.geometry:
        within = point.within(sh)
        in_shape.append(within)
    return df.loc[in_shape.index(True), 'area'], df.loc[in_shape.index(True), 'area_code'], df.loc[in_shape.index(True), 'average_income']


houses['mean_district_income'] = 0
houses['district_code'] = 0

not_assigned = []
for row, value in tqdm(houses.iterrows()):
    try:
        result = find_district(Point(houses.loc[row, 'long'], houses.loc[row, 'lat']), all_t_data)
        houses.loc[row, 'city_district'] = result[0]
        houses.loc[row, 'mean_district_income'] = result[2]
        houses.loc[row, 'district_code'] = result[1]
        time.sleep(0.1)
    except:
        not_assigned.append(row)
        
# Not assigned houses
print(not_assigned)

The Prices and Income data are positively skewed which probably affect results on the map. However, normality is an important assumption for many statistical techniques. We decided to explore the scipy.stats package in order to find an appropriate power transformer.


A Box Cox transformation is a transformation of non-normal variable into a normal variable. The Box Cox transformation is based on 1964 paper of George Box and Sir David Roxbee Cox who developed the technique.



















In [43]:



     


plt.figure(1, figsize=[16,3])

ax1=plt.subplot(1,2,1)
x = all_t_data['average_income']
stats.probplot(x, dist=stats.norm, plot=ax1)
ax1.set_xlabel('Quantiles')
ax1.set_ylabel('Average Income')
ax1.set_title('Probplot against normal distribution', pad=30)


ax2=plt.subplot(1,2,2)
boxcox_lambda = stats.boxcox_normmax(x, brack=(-1.9, 2.0),  method='mle')
transformed_array = stats.boxcox(x, boxcox_lambda)
stats.probplot(transformed_array, dist=stats.norm , plot=ax2)
ax2.set_xlabel('Quantiles')
ax2.set_ylabel('Average Income')
ax2.set_title('Probplot against normal distribution after Box-Cox transformation', pad=30)

# transform data
all_t_data['average_income_transformed'] = transformed_array
# To transform back
# np.exp(np.log(boxcox_lambda*transformed_array+1)/boxcox_lambda)

plt.figure(2, figsize=[16,3])
sns.distplot(all_t_data['average_income_transformed'], fit=stats.norm)
plt.title('Distribution of Transformed Income in GTA', pad=30)
plt.xlabel('Transformed Income in GTA', labelpad=20)
plt.ylabel('Probablity Density', labelpad=20)
(mu, sigma) = stats.norm.fit(all_t_data['average_income_transformed'])
plt.legend(['Normal dist. ($\mu=$ {:.2f} and $\sigma=$ {:.2f} )'.format(mu, sigma)],
            loc='best')

plt.figure(3, figsize=[16,3])

ax3=plt.subplot(1,2,1)
x = houses_income['list_price']
stats.probplot(x, dist=stats.norm, plot=ax3)
ax3.set_xlabel('Quantiles')
ax3.set_ylabel('House Price')
ax3.set_title('Probplot vs normal distribution', pad=30)


ax4=plt.subplot(1,2,2)
boxcox_lambda = stats.boxcox_normmax(x, brack=(-1.9, 2.0),  method='mle')
transformed_array = stats.boxcox(x, boxcox_lambda)
stats.probplot(transformed_array, dist=stats.norm , plot=ax4)
ax4.set_xlabel('Quantiles')
ax4.set_ylabel('House Price')
ax4.set_title('Probplot vs normal distribution after Box-Cox transformation', pad=30)

houses_income['final_price_transformed'] = transformed_array

6. Data Pre-processing¶
The sold price (“Sold_on”) and tax data (“tax”) are two other useful features. The tax column contains the yearly tax amount for each house.


In addition, the month from the “Sold_on” was extracted and added as a separate column to the dataset (“month_sold”).

This graph shows that according to ExtraTreesRegressor function, the most effective feature is sqft_avg. The other most important feature is tax. Since there were some missing tax values which were replaced with zero, the result of model could be adversely affected by these zero values. It is important to make better estimations on this features. KNN Imputer was used to estimate the missing values of taxes (replaced by zero) based on nearest neighbour properties.



















In [53]:



     


# load original house_income data
houses_income = pd.read_csv('houses_with_income.csv', index_col='title')

# extract months of sold
houses_income['month_sold'] = pd.to_datetime(houses_income['Sold on'],  errors='coerce').dt.month
# clean the tax column
houses_income['tax'] = houses_income['tax'].str.strip().str.replace('$','').str.replace(',','').str.replace(' /yr','')
# replace "No Data" with Nan in tax column
for index, row in houses_income.iterrows():
    if row['tax'] == 'No Data':
        houses_income.loc[index, 'tax'] = np.nan
    else:
        try:
            houses_income.loc[index, 'tax'] = float(row['tax'])
        except:
            print(row['tax'])

# convert categorical features

y = [a[1] for a in sorted_feature_importance]

plt.scatter(x,y)
plt.xlabel('Importance of Features', labelpad=20)
plt.title('Feature Importances', pad=30)
plt.show()



     






















    
    



































With all of the adjustments made, the importance of features changed significantly. Now, we have the tax data as the second most important feature and the bathrooms and bedrooms as the third and fourth one contributing to the price of the houses.


"Cross correlation is a way to measure the degree of similarity between features. This type of correlation is useful to calculate because it can tell us if the values of one feature are predictive of the future values of another feature. 
Correlation matrix helps us to discover the bivariate relationship between independent variables in a dataset." The range of the correlation coefficient is from -1 to +1. The closer the cross-correlation value is to -1 or 1, the more closely the sets are co-related.



















In [61]:



     


# Create features Heatmap to see how feature are correlated with final_price
def correlantion_heatmap(df, center = None):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = [14,12])
    colormap = sns.diverging_palette(11, 220, as_cmap=True)
    fig = sns.heatmap(df.corr(),
                cmap = colormap,
               center = center,
                annot = True,
                linewidths = 0.1,
                annot_kws={'fontsize':12})
    plt.title('Correlantion Heatmap', pad=30)
    
all_train = y_train.to_frame().join(X_train, how='left')
correlantion_heatmap(all_train, center=0)



     






















    
    



































To some extend there are co-relation between some features. For instance, the number of bathrooms and sqft are co-related.

from sklearn import preprocessing

scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit(X_train)

X_train_scaled = scaler.transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)



     























Training preliminary models as benchmark¶






















At this stage, all the required elements to build the linear model are ready. The next step is to proceed building the preliminary model using scikit-learn module. Three different linear regression models were built and trained including OLS, Bayesian and Elastic Net. The process for all models were the same. To store the model algorithm, a variable is defined. Then, the train set variables was fitted into the model and the predictions were made.



















In [67]:



     


from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression # OLS algorithm
from sklearn.linear_model import BayesianRidge # Bayesian algorithm
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet # ElasticNet algorithm


from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error # evaluation of errors
from sklearn.metrics import explained_variance_score as evs # evaluation metric
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score as r2 # evaluation metric



     



















In [68]:



     


# OLS
ols = LinearRegression()
ols.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
ols_yhat = ols.predict(X_test_scaled)
ols_test_error = mean_squared_error(y_test, ols_yhat)
print('OLS test RMSE: ${}'.format(ols_test_error))

# Bayesian
bayesian = BayesianRidge()
bayesian.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
bayesian_yhat = bayesian.predict(X_test_scaled)
bayesian_test_error = mean_squared_error(y_test, bayesian_yhat)
print('Bayesian test RMSE: ${}'.format(bayesian_test_error))

# ElasticNet
en = ElasticNet(alpha = 0.01)
en.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
en_yhat = en.predict(X_test_scaled)
en_test_error = mean_squared_error(y_test, en_yhat)
print('ElasticNet test RMSE: ${}'.format(en_test_error))



     






















    
    






OLS test RMSE: $123322777829.73291
Bayesian test RMSE: $123337868887.263
ElasticNet test RMSE: $123470698458.30493




























Using the algorithms provided by scikit-learn, we have successfully built five different linear regression models. Now, to know which model is more appropriate for our data, we can evaluate each of the models using the evaluation metrics and come to a conclusion.























Evaluation of benchmark models¶
When it comes to the ‘explained_variance_score’ metric, the score should not below 0.60 or 60%. If it is the case, then our built model is not sufficient for our data to solve the given case. So, the ideal score of the ‘explained_variance_score’ should be between 0.60 and 1.0.



















In [69]:



     


# estimate the explained variance score

print('-------------------------------------------------------------------------------')

print('-------------------------------------------------------------------------------')
print('Explained Variance Score of Bayesian model is {}'.format(evs(y_test, bayesian_yhat)))
print('-------------------------------------------------------------------------------')
print('Explained Variance Score of ElasticNet is {}'.format(evs(y_test, en_yhat)))

All models scored around 74% which means all of them can be used to solve this problem. The score for Bayesian regression model, not by a huge margin, is slightly better than others


‘r2_score’ (R-squared) metric is the next evaluation metric that was used. R-squared is a measurement of how well the dependent variable explains the variance of the independent variable. R-squared is among the most popular evaluation metric for regression models. The suitable ‘r2_score’ should be at least 0.60.

7. Conclusion¶






















Considering the new situation in property market, there were questions about the prediction of housing price in the city of Toronto. The used pricing database was produced using zolo.com which is one of the most popular online realtor websites. To access the database please click on this link. This dataset includes information on the sold property from 2021 to 2022. 
In order to include neighborhood data in our analysis, we used the open data portal of the City of Toronto. The Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) was used to study the data and relations between features and their prices. EDA helped to identify the most relevant features affecting the housing price. 
The merged dataset was split into training and test datasets. The training dataset was used to fit machine learning algorithms.
